25|$|The {{generalization}} to functions taking {{values in}} any normed vector space is straightforward (replacing absolute values by norms), where f and g need not take their {{values in the}} same space. A generalization to functions g taking values in any <b>topological</b> <b>group</b> is also possible.|$|E
25|$|As a {{homotopy}} theory, {{the notion}} of covering spaces works well when the deck transformation group is discrete, or, equivalently, when the space is locally path-connected. However, when the deck transformation group is a <b>topological</b> <b>group</b> whose topology is not discrete, difficulties arise. Some {{progress has been made}} for more complex spaces, such as the Hawaiian earring; see the references there for further information.|$|E
50|$|A {{relatively}} refined {{theory is}} available for pseudocompact <b>topological</b> <b>groups.</b> In particular, W. W. Comfort and Kenneth A. Ross proved that a product of pseudocompact <b>topological</b> <b>groups</b> is still pseudocompact (this might fail for arbitrary topological spaces).|$|R
