500|$|The [...] "restricted" [...] {{version of}} Hilbert's fifth problem (solved by Gleason) asks, more specifically, whether every locally Euclidean <b>topological</b> <b>group</b> is a Lie group. That is, if a group G has the {{structure}} of a topological manifold, can that structure be strengthened to a real analytic structure, so that within any neighborhood of an element of G, the group law is defined by a convergent power series, and so that overlapping neighborhoods have compatible power series definitions? Prior to Gleason's work, special cases of the problem had been solved by Luitzen Egbertus Jan Brouwer, John von Neumann, Lev Pontryagin, and Garrett Birkhoff, among others.|$|E
